ef="https://t.co/Y1gwob4ZKj">pic.twitter.com/Y1gwob4ZKj</a></p><p> — Rogue Variable (@Adino111) <a href="https://twitter.com/Adino111/status/1890146415411892590?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">February 13, 2025</a> </p></blockquote><p><script async src="https://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script></p><p> While films such as <em>Gladiator</em> and the recent <a href="https://www.nme.com/news/film/christopher-lee-back-as-saruman-in-new-lord-of-the-rings-film-thanks-to-archival-recordings-3807679#:~:text=The%20first%20Lord%20of%20the,recordings%20of%20Lee's%20line%20readings."><em>Lord Of The Rings animation</em></a> have brought deceased actors back through old footage, this rendering of Morita was completely digital. “There&#39;s no archival footage in there” confirmed Heald. “We shot Don, the fight and the entrance practically. So that existed in camera. There&#39;s a VFX company that has a deepfake technology”.</p><p> He continued: “You apply an AI filter that uses archival audio from Pat Morita to get that voice dialled as close as possible. At the end of the day, you&#39;re not actually recreating a person. We&#39;re paying homage to a hero, and you&#39;re trying to get as close as possible, while the audience knows that obviously he&#39;s not really there.”</p><p> The finale of <em>Cobra Kai</em> was met with positive reviews, with critics not entirely convinced by the cameo but ultimately saying <a href="https://www.nme.com/news/tv/critics-praise-cobra-kai-finale-mr-miyagi-himself-would-be-proud-3837771">“Mr. Miyagi himself would be proud”</a> .</p><p> The post<a href="https://www.nme.com/news/tv/cobra-kai-brought-back-pat-moritas-mr-miyagi-using-ai-3838133">&#39;Cobra Kai&#39; brought back Pat Morita&#39;s Mr Miyagi using AI</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.nme.com">NME</a> .</p> ;
